From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Sun, 21 Jun 2026 07:30:48 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] find: resolve against the logical cwd, drop the
 unshare/thread hack
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Completes the "no unshare; use logical state" rule for the in-process tools.
find's walkdir traversal resolves against AT_FDCWD, so the old builtin ran on
a worker thread that unshare(CLONE_FS)+chdir'd to give itself a private kernel
cwd. That mechanism is gone.

Mechanism (vendored fork): `Dependencies::cwd()` supplies the shell's logical
working dir. When set, `process_dir` roots a RELATIVE start path at that
absolute dir — an absolute walk that never reads or mutates the process cwd —
and remaps each entry's DISPLAY path back to the start-relative form. The
split is deliberate: `WalkEntry::path()` stays the real absolute path so every
fs op and cached metadata stay correct (-delete, -empty, -lname, -type, …),
while a new `display_path()` is used only by the display/match sites
(-print/-print0, -path/-ipath, -regex, -printf %p/%P/%h, and -exec {}). A
normal -exec child runs with the logical cwd as its current_dir so the
relative {} resolves; -execdir keeps "./basename" + the real parent dir.
Standalone (cwd == None) is unchanged — walks the path as given.

The builtin now runs find_main in-process on the calling thread (no thread, no
unshare); catch_unwind preserves panic isolation. This removes the find part
of the previous fail-loud H2 change — there is no longer any process cwd to
get wrong.

Verified in a box: relative display (`.`/`sub`, no trailing slash), -name,
-path, -type f/l (cached metadata), relative subdir start, multiple starts,
-printf %p/%f/%h, -exec {} (\; and +) resolving in the logical cwd, -execdir
in the real parent, absolute start (no remap), and -delete removing the real
file. xargs unregressed.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
